Categorical handedness (primary)

Summary

When handedness is binned as left (EHI <= -40) or right (EHI > +40):
Do we find an interaction of field x level x handedness?
At the local level, do left handers show significantly different hemifield bias than right handers? (Local: field x handedness)
At the local level, what is each group’s field bias? (Local: By handedness group, effect of field)

For reaction time, LVF global>local bias was significantly reduced in left handers ( = 529, EHI <= -40) compared to right handers (= 413, EHI >= +40; difference between groups = 20.51ms, 95% CI [10.45, 30.57], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 15.98, < .0001, two-sided). Both groups showed significant LVF global>local bias: for right handers, the effect size was 44.09ms (95% CI [36.54, 51.63], (111,144.6) = 11.46, = < .0001, two-sided); for left handers, 23.57ms (95% CI [16.92, 30.23], (111,144.1) = 6.94, < .0001, two-sided.

within the local level, left handers showed reduced hemifield bias, in the direction predicted by AAH: right handers responded faster to local stimuli in the RVF than LVF by 18.16ms (95% CI [12.75, 23.57], (111,145.9) = 6.58, <.0001, two-sided), whereas left handers responded (insignificantly) faster to local stimuli in the LVF than RVF by 0.56ms (95% CI [-4.21, 5.33], (111,145.6) = 0.23, = .82, two-sided; difference = 18.72ms, 95% CI [11.51, 26.83], (111,145.78) = 5.09, <.0001, two-sided).

Stats

Reaction time is modeled as a linear effect of field, level, and handedness, using data from every target-present trial with a “go” response:

lmer( rt ~ field*level*handedness + (1 | subject) )

Categorical handedness (exploratory)

Summary

When handedness is binned as left (EHI <= -100) or right (EHI > +100):
Do we find an interaction of field x level x handedness?
At the local level, do left handers show significantly different hemifield bias than right handers? (Local: field x handedness)
At the local level, what is each group’s field bias? (Local: By handedness group, effect of field)

Limiting analysis to strong left and right handers with EHI scores of +/-100, left handers’ LVF>RVF global bias was reduced by 17.44ms (95% CI [1.50, 33.38], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 4.6, = .032, two-sided). Both groups showed significant LVF global>local bias: for right handers, the effect size was 36.96ms (95% CI [25.36 ,48.56], (44,479.7) = 6.25, < .0001, two-sided); for left handers, 19.52ms (95% CI [8.58, 30.45], (44,479.0) = 3.50, = .0005, two-sided).

within the local level, right and left handers showed reversed hemifield bias: right handers responded faster to local stimuli in the RVF than LVF by 9.97ms (95% CI [1.61, 18.32], (44,479.9) = 2.34, = .019, two-sided), whereas left handers responded faster to local stimuli in the LVF than RVF by 7.98ms (95% CI [0.14, 15.83], (44,479.4) = 2.00 = .046, two-sided; difference = 17.95ms, 95% CI [6.48, 29.41], (44,479.7) = 3.07, = .002, two-sided).

Plots

Continuous handedness (primary)

Summary

Do we find an interaction of field x level x handedness (continuous EHI score)?

With handedness treated as continuous, we found that degree of left handedness predicted reduced LVF global>local bias (0.13ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [0.06, 0.19], \(\chi^2(1)\) = 17.88, < .0001, two-sided). Estimated LVF global>local bias for EHI +100 (strong right handers) was 45.61ms (95% CI [37.73, 53.48]), and for EHI -100 (strong left handers), 19.92ms (95% CI [12.72, 27.12]), a difference of 25.69ms.

within the local level, left handedness predicted reduced RVF bias (0.12ms per EHI unit, 95% CI [0.07, 0.18], (131,342.5) = 5.65, = < .0001, two-sided). Strong right handers (EHI = +100) showed estimated RVF bias of 21.36ms (95% CI [15.70, 27.01]), and strong left handers (EHI = -100) showed estimated LVF bias of 3.28ms (95% CI [-1.88, 8.43]), a difference of 24.54ms.

Model RT as a linear effect of field, level, and EHI (continuous):

rt_model_ehi <- lmer( rt ~ field*level*ehi + (1 | subject) )
